{"result": "**Entities:**\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Planning variance\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Planning variance refers to the difference between what was expected and what actually happened due to factors outside the control of the organization.\")##\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Market share variance\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Market share variance is the difference between the actual sales and the budgeted market share of the actual market.\")##\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Advantages of variance analysis\"<|>\"features\"<|>\"Advantages of variance analysis include distinguishing between variances caused by bad planning or unavoidable factors and those resulting from operating factors, providing feedback control on processes needing correction, updating standards to current conditions, and improving motivation by assessing managers only on variances under their control.\")##\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Disadvantages of variance analysis\"<|>\"features\"<|>\"Disadvantages of variance analysis include extra data requirements, being time-consuming, potential manipulation by managers claiming external causes for adverse variances and internal causes for favorable variances, and operational managers blaming poor standard setting for adverse variances.\")##\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Manipulation of budgets and standards\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Manipulation of budgets and standards refers to the revision of budgets and standards at the end of the year to hide adverse variances, which should be prevented by strict rules and independent, verifiable evidence.\")##\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Effect on staff motivation and action\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Effect on staff motivation and action refers to how variance analysis and standard costing can impact the motivation of managers and staff, potentially leading to morale issues if used insensitively, and causing employees to conceal adverse variances or take actions that may not be in the company's best interests.\")##\n\n(\"entity\"<|>\"Performance evaluation using variances\"<|>\"concepts\"